<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26268l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26268l">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26268l"> 268(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> first &amp; last &pound;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Institutions of the Private Law. Mancipation]</font>&mdash;<font color="green">[As]</font> attendance during all the time that some thousands of pounds, perhaps of copper, were being weighed would have been an intolerable burden upon the five citizens convoked <font color="green">[as witnesses of the mancipation]</font>, it may be surmised that it early became a common practice to have the price weighed beforehand, and then only to reweigh, or pretend to reweigh, before the witnesses only a single little bit of metal (<i>raudusculum</i>), which the transferee then handed to the transferrer as &ldquo;<mark>the first pound and the last</mark>,&rdquo; and thus representative of the whole. And where no real price was intended, as in constiting a <i>dos</i> or in coemption, a <i>raudusculum</i> would also be employed. <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 532</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
